<styl>by <m0>By LYDIA MARTIN<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Staff Writer<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>P<m2><ql>
<m0>rincess Kitty's toys are still scattered all over Karen Payne's South Miami townhouse (--) her rubber balls, her feathers, her scratching post. Her bowls are still on the floor in the kitchen.<ep>
   Her little wagon, the tiny pink chair she sat in, the sequined dresses and bathing suits and bonnets she wore when she performed, are all still out.<ep>
   Her ashes rest on an altar draped in pink satin in the middle of the living room, inside a pretty tin box with a white ceramic cat angel sitting on top. Beside it, always, are fresh flowers from the florist. <ep>
   But then, Princess Kitty, who died Dec. 21 at age 10, wasn't just any cat. <ep>
   She was a cat with her own newspaper column and international fan club. A cat who could play <m0>Three Blind Mice <m0> on a toy piano, slam-dunk a mini-basketball through a hoop, jump high hurdles. A cat who could put any dog to shame in the sit-stay-fetch department. She played Hemingway's favorite cat in the 1988 TV miniseries <m0>Hemingway<m0>, starring Stacey Keach; she starred in a Florida Lotto commercial last year promoting the Fishfinder's game; she posed for the cover of Cat Fancy magazine in 1990.<ep>
   As felines go, she led an extraordinary life. Perhaps that is why her death has been such a blow to her owner.<ep>
   Not that Payne, a former Miami News reporter who is now editor of the Miami-based Honeymoon magazine, would consider herself Princess Kitty's <m0>owner.<m0> She was more Kitty's friend, her companion, her partner.<ep>
  ``Princess Kitty's death broke <m2><ql>
<ql>
PLEASE SEE  PRINCESS,  3D<qr>
<m4>--7.610 inches ( 45p10 )--from start of measuring to here--<m2><ql>
